  "text": "A particular challenge in typology is acquiring and using universally available variables that reflect the nature of interactions among environmental forces, geomorphic structure, and biotic composition and function --all of which determine flux characteristics. An initial effort within the LOICZ project collected over 30 global data sets of variables relevant to coastal studies, and organized the data into a system of coastal-zone grid cells for investigation of their utility in the coastal typology effort (http://www.nioz.nl/loicz --link ref). As the LOICZ data collection approach evolved into a more geographically extensive system of half-degree cells and additional variables 3 (http://www.kgs.ukans.edu/Hexacoral/Envirodata), it became apparent that specific identification and classification of the shoreline was needed. The World Vector Shoreline [CITATION_1] captures the geographical form of the world's coastlines, and can be used to derive measures of coastal complexity. Coastal complexity (the degree of sinuosity or tortuosity of a coastline) is an attractive candidate for the typology project because it is widely recognized as an important modifier of both biotic community structure (e.g., [CITATION_2] and water residence time. \"Exposure\" or \"openness\", a function of coastline complexity, are common criteria in habitat classification schemes.",
